idase activity","Suppresses viral protein synthesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOseltamivir works by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing viral neuraminidase activity\u003C/strong\u003E. Neuraminidase is an enzyme on the surface of influenza viruses that cleaves sialic acid residues, allowing newly formed viral particles to detach from infected cells. By inhibiting this enzyme, oseltamivir prevents the release and spread of new viral particles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks viral entry into host cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not the mechanism of oseltamivir. Viral entry involves haemagglutinin binding to sialic acid receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits viral RNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of other antivirals like favipiravir, not oseltamivir\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppresses viral protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Oseltamivir does not interfere with viral protein production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts viral capsid assembly\u003C/strong\u003E - Oseltamivir acts on viral release, not on viral assembly\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing the release of new viral particles, oseltamivir reduces viral spread within the respiratory tract and helps limit the duration and severity of influenza infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oseltamivir works by inhibiting viral neuraminidase, preventing the release of new influenza virions from infected cells.","Neuraminidase inhibitors are effective against both influenza A and B viruses.","Blocking viral release helps reduce viral spread to neighbouring cells and limits the duration of infection."],"references":["Davies, B et al. Pharmacokinetics of oseltamivir: an oral antiviral for the treatment and prophylaxis 